00:18:00.000 --> 00:18:04.000
like this gives me a very reliable estimate here.

00:18:04.000 --> 00:18:10.000
So looking pretty good, like in terms of I have not overfit my data here.

00:18:10.000 --> 00:18:15.000
One thing that might be interesting, this particular data is towns in the U.K.,

00:18:15.000 --> 00:18:20.000
and so it might be interesting depending on, you know,

00:18:20.000 --> 00:18:25.000
like how these things are related to each other spatially.

00:18:25.000 --> 00:18:28.000
It might be interesting instead of doing something like bootstraps,

00:18:28.000 --> 00:18:32.000
do a spatial resampling approach so that –

00:18:32.000 --> 00:18:36.000
and what that would do is that educational attainment,

00:18:36.000 --> 00:18:41.000
like I'm sure so much else in the world, exhibits spatial autocorrelation,

00:18:41.000 --> 00:18:45.000
where things that are close together tend to be more similar to each other.

00:18:45.000 --> 00:18:47.000
And so if you do random sampling,

00:18:47.000 --> 00:18:51.000
you actually can get a slightly overoptimistic approach for that.

00:18:51.000 --> 00:18:52.000
We're not going to dig into that today,

00:18:52.000 --> 00:18:55.000
